Due to the complexity of the system of partial differential equations, it may be more efficient to use a finite difference method for numerical simulations. However, a simpler approach using ODE solver can be used for analyzing the stability of the steady-state solutions.

Here is an example code for Matlab:

%%%%%%% Parameters %%%%%%%%

% Intrinsic growth rate
r = 0.5;

% Carrying capacity
K = 1;

% Diffusion coefficient for population density
D = 0.1;

% Constant determining effect of information density
a = -0.2;

% Diffusion coefficient for information density
C = 0.05;

% Spatial domain
L = 20;
N = 100;

x = linspace(0, L, N+1);
y = linspace(0, K*2, N+1);

%%%%%%% Reaction terms %%%%%%%%

% Logistic growth model for population
f = @(y, x) r*y.*(1 - y/K);

% Linear model for information density
g = @(y, x) a*x;

%%%%%%% ODE system %%%%%%%%

% Define ODE system for y and x
dydt = @(t, yx) [f(yx(1), yx(2)); 0] + [D*diff(yx(1,:),2); 0];
dxdt = @(t, yx) [0; g(yx(1), yx(2))] + [0; C*diff(yx(2,:),2)];

% Define initial conditions
y0 = 0.5*ones(1, N+1);
x0 = zeros(1, N+1);
yx0 = [y0; x0];

% Define time range and solve ODE system
tspan = [0, 50];
[t, yx] = ode45(@(t, yx) [dydt(t, yx); dxdt(t, yx)], tspan, yx0);

%%%%%%% Plot results %%%%%%%%
subplot(2,1,1)
surf(x, t, yx(:,1:N+1))
xlabel('x')
ylabel('t')
zlabel('y')
title('Population density')

subplot(2,1,2)
surf(x, t, yx(:,N+2:end))
xlabel('x')
ylabel('t')
zlabel('x')
title('Information density')

This code defines the parameters and reaction terms, and then solves the ODE system using the built-in ODE45 solver in Matlab. The results are plotted as surface plots of population density and information density over time and space.

Note that since the system is nonlinear and complex, the stability of the steady-state solutions may depend on the initial conditions and the diffusion coefficients. It is advisable to explore the parameter space and perform sensitivity analyses to fully understand the behavior of the system.

We can write a MATLAB code to solve the system of partial differential equations using the "pdepe" function, which solves parabolic and elliptic partial differential equations in one or two spatial dimensions.

First, we define the reaction terms and diffusion coefficients as anonymous functions:

r = 0.5; % intrinsic growth rate
K = 10; % carrying capacity
a = -0.1; % effect of information density on population growth
D = 0.1; % diffusion coefficient for population density
C = 0.05; % diffusion coefficient for information density

f = @(t, y, x) r.*y.*(1 - y./K); % reaction term for population density
g = @(t, y, x) a.*x; % reaction term for information density
Dp = @(t, y, x) D; % diffusion coefficient for population density
Cp = @(t, y, x) C; % diffusion coefficient for information density

Next, we set the spatial and time domain:

x = linspace(0, 20, 100); % spatial domain
t = linspace(0, 100, 1000); % time domain

We can now define the initial and boundary conditions for the population and information densities. For simplicity, we choose the initial and boundary conditions to be uniform:

y0 = 0.1*ones(size(x)); % initial population density
x0 = zeros(size(x)); % initial information density

bcfun = @(ya, yb) [ya(1); yb(1); ya(2); yb(2)]; % boundary conditions

We can now call the "pdepe" function to solve the system of partial differential equations:

