Here is a sample code for MATLAB to simulate the system of equations for this reaction-diffusion model.

```matlab
% Reaction-Diffusion Model for Human Population Growth and Information Density
clear; close all; clc;

% Parameters
r = 0.1; % Intrinsic growth rate
K = 100; % Carrying capacity
a = 0.05; % Constant for information density effect on population growth
D = 1; % Diffusion coefficient for population density
C = 1; % Diffusion coefficient for information density

% Discretization
Nx = 100; % Number of grid points in x-direction
Ny = 100; % Number of grid points in y-direction
Lx = 10; % Domain length in x-direction
Ly = 10; % Domain length in y-direction
dx = Lx/Nx; % Grid step in x-direction
dy = Ly/Ny; % Grid step in y-direction
dt = 0.01; % Time step
T = 100; % Total simulation time
Nt = round(T/dt); % Number of time steps

% Initialize grids
y_grid = zeros(Nx+2, Ny+2, 2);
x_grid = zeros(Nx+2, Ny+2, 2);
x_grid(2:end-1,2:end-1,1) = 1; % Initial information density distribution

% Time-stepping loop
for t = 1:Nt
    % Update population density (y)
    laplacian_y = (y_grid(1:end-2,2:end-1,t) - 2*y_grid(2:end-1,2:end-1,t) + y_grid(3:end,2:end-1,t))/dx^2 ...
                + (y_grid(2:end-1,1:end-2,t) - 2*y_grid(2:end-1,2:end-1,t) + y_grid(2:end-1,3:end,t))/dy^2;
    f_y = r * y_grid(2:end-1,2:end-1,t) .* (1 - y_grid(2:end-1,2:end-1,t)/K);
    y_grid(2:end-1, 2:end-1, 3 - t) = y_grid(2:end-1, 2:end-1, t) + dt * (f_y + D * laplacian_y);

    % Update information density (x)
    laplacian_x = (x_grid(1:end-2,2:end-1,t) - 2*x_grid(2:end-1,2:end-1,t) + x_grid(3:end,2:end-1,t))/dx^2 ...
                + (x_grid(2:end-1,1:end-2,t) - 2*x_grid(2:end-1,2:end-1,t) + x_grid(2:end-1,3:end,t))/dy^2;
    g_x = a * x_grid(2:end-1, 2:end-1, t);
    x_grid(2:end-1, 2:end-1, 3 - t) = x_grid(2:end-1, 2:end-1, t) + dt * (g_x + C * laplacian_x);

    % Periodic boundary conditions
    y_grid([1 end], 2:end-1, 3 - t) = y_grid([end-1 2], 2:end-1, 2);
    y_grid(2:end-1, [1 end], 3 - t) = y_grid(2:end-1, [end-1 2], 2);
    x_grid([1 end], 2:end-1, 3 - t) = x_grid([end-1 2], 2:end-1, 2);
    x_grid(2:end-1, [1 end], 3 - t) = x_grid(2:end-1, [end-1 2], 2);

    % Exchange old and new grids
    t = 3 - t;
end

% Plot results
figure;
subplot(1,2,1);
imagesc(y_grid(2:end-1,2:end-1,1));
colorbar;
title('Population Density (y)');
xlabel('x');
ylabel('y');

subplot(1,2,2);
imagesc(x_grid(2:end-1,2:end-1,1));
colorbar;
title('Information Density (x)');
xlabel('x');
ylabel('y');
```

This code sets up the reaction-diffusion system and solves it using a simple finite difference scheme with periodic boundary conditions. It then plots the steady-state solutions for the population density (y) and information density (x) in the spatial domain. Note that you may need to adjust the parameters and the initial conditions to observe the different behaviors of the system, as discussed in the previous answers.

